[underline]Geology[/underline]
[underline]Volcanoes[/underline]
By far the greatest changes produced upon
the solid parts of the surface of the Globe in late
times [underline]have resulted[/underline] from the agencies of Volcanic
fires.
The causes and the [underline]effects[/underline] of Volcanoes are
subjects which cannot fail to excite curiosity
in all minds attached to the knowledge of
Nature
And their importance in Geological Theory
is great and distinct; for they afford the
only known facts of the agency [underline]of Heat[/underline]

[page]8|MS-DAVY-11705-000-00008|dnp17e04pp|95148880[/page]
[underline]upon rocks which occur[/underline] in a great scale
and their relations to general Theory are
numerous and interesting. -
Volcanic fires have operated to a great extent
in all quarters of the Globe and they appear to
have occurred in the earliest ages of which we
have any authentic records -
[underline]Pindar[/underline] who lived nearly 500 years before
the [underline]Christian era[/underline] mentioned the [underline]eruptions of Etna[/underline]
and blending descriptions of this great natural
event with poetic fable He attributes the
effect to Typheas who after being defeated
[insertion]by Jupiter[/insertion] in the wars of the Gods at [deletion]by Jupiter[/deletion]
was supposed in the ancient mythology

[page]9|MS-DAVY-11705-000-00009|dnp17e05pp|95148881[/page]
to have been buried under Sicily.
The passage is one of the finest in [underline]the odes[/underline]
I shall read a few lines of it in wests translation
Now under sulpherous cumus sea bound shore
And vast Sicilia lies his shaggy breast
And snowy etna nurse of endless frost
The eternal prop of heaven for ever burst
Forth from whose nitrous caverns issuing rise
Pure liquid fountains of tempestuous fire
And veil in ruddy mists the noon day skies
Whilst cloaked in smoke the eddying flames
aspire.

[page]10|MS-DAVY-11705-000-00010|dnp17e06pp|95148882[/page]
Amongst the greek historians Thucidides
mentions a great eruption of [underline]Etna[/underline] which
took place 476 years before Christ but he
gives no minute details.
Of the greek naturalist Aristotle in his
or concerning wonderful reports states that
had heard of fires which burnt by night and
issued out of the Earth in the Eolian Isles
and he was perfectly well acquainted with
the volcanoes of Sicily. -
The first eruption of Vesuvius certainly
known to have taken place was in the 79
year after the Christian era that eruption
in which the Elder Pliny lost his life.

[page]11|MS-DAVY-11705-000-00011|dnp17e07pp|95148883[/page]
But Diodorus Siculus and Strabo who were
both born before the death of Julius Caesar, were
of opinion that the mountain had burnt in
remote ages -
And that this must have been the case is
evident from the circumstances of [underline]Pompeia[/underline]
and [underline]Herculaneum[/underline] cities which were destroyed
in the first recorded [underline]eruption[/underline] being principa[insertion]lly[/insertion]
of Lava
The ancient Philosophers seems to have
paid very little attention to the natural
History of Volcanoes -
-And even amongst the moderns till
within the last forty years it has been
but little an object of study. -

[page]12|MS-DAVY-11705-000-00012|dnp17e08pp|95148884[/page]
- Sir W[superscript]m[/superscript] Hamilton was one of the first
persons who endeavoured to direct the observation
of men of [underline]science to the subject[/underline] -
His remarks upon Vesuvius published in ph[superscript]l[/superscript]
Tran[superscript]s[/superscript] - are well known and his work on the
Phligrean fields equally demonstrate the extent
of his knowledge and the refinement of his taste
- Since the period in which the first remarks
of our celebrated Countryman were made Known
to this world the path that He has marked out
has been pursued by many Philosophical
[underline]observations[/underline] -
Since that time Spallanzani has given
many valuable remarks on volcanoes in
his work entitled travels into the two Sicilies -

[page]13|MS-DAVY-11705-000-00013|dnp17e09pp|95148885[/page]
Breslac has added considerably to our geological
knowledge of them by his observations on
Campania
And Ferber and Dolomieu have both treated
with great acuteness the mineralogy of this
branch of Science
And if the most instructive of the works upon
the subject were to be selected it would
perhaps be the treatise of Dolomieu
sur les isles on the Lipari Islands
In this publication the most [underline]minute[/underline]
[underline]observations[/underline] may be found combined with
the most [underline]enlarged views[/underline]
And the Author has enlightened his
Philosophical researches by the assistance of
the most refined methods of Chemistry -

[page]14|MS-DAVY-11705-000-00014|dnp17e10pp|95148886[/page]
The forms of Volcanic mountains are
usually conical and those Rocks which
constitute their bases and which have not
been altered by fire differ very much
in their nature in different districts
The strata that appears at the [underline]foot[/underline] of
[underline]Vesuvius[/underline] are principlly [underline]shell Limestone[/underline]
The foundations of Etna are said to be
[underline]granite[/underline] and [underline]porphyry[/underline]; And these
[underline]substances[/underline] according to the reports of
Humboldt constitute the bases of the
great Volcanic chain of the Andes
[deletion]some [underline]of the eminences[/underline][/deletion]

