The lower regions of volcanic mountains
even when the substratum of the soil is
lava are usually exceedingly fertile
and when a long continued quiet has prevailed
in [underline]the interior[/underline] vegetation is vigorous upon
all parts of the surface that are not raised
above the line of perpetual snow
In the account given of the Crater of
Vesuvius by Bracchni the interior of
mountain is described as in the form of
the inverted hollow of a cone covered
with luxuriant vegetation and abounding

