I accepted (says the Auther) the invitation
of the Bishop of Catania to stay a day with
him so that I might be the better able to
inform your Majesty of the extraordinary
fire which comes from [underline]Mount Etna 15 miles[/underline]
distant from that City, which from the
horridness of its aspect for the vast quantity
thereof (for it is 15 miles in length and 7
in breadth) for its monstrous devastation
and quick progress may be terme an
inundation of fire a flood of fire and
glowing stones burning with such rage
as to advance into the sea 600 yards
and that to a mile in breadth which

[page]39|MS-DAVY-11705-000-00039|dnp17e35pp|95148911[/page]
I saw -
And that which did [deletion]agu[/deletion] augment my
admiration was to see in the sea this matter
like rugged rocks burning in four fathoms
of water and two fathoms higher than
the waves -
Some parts liquid throwing off the stones
about them and causing a great and horrible
noise in the water and other parts becoming
solid making a firm foundation -
When it was night I went upon the Tower
and I could plainly see at ten miles distance
the fire [underline]descending[/underline] from the mountain
in a direct line; and the flame ascending
as high as the greatest steeple in your
Majestys Kingdom and throwing great stones
into the air -

[page]40|MS-DAVY-11705-000-00040|dnp17e36pp|95148912[/page]
And I could discern the rivers of fire
flowing down from the mountain of
a bright red colour bearing upon it
great stones of a paler red -
I assure your Majesty no pen can
express how terrible it was nor could all
the Art or industry in the world have
quenched it or diverted its course.
In forty days time it had destroyed the
habitations of 27.000 persons made two
hills of a thousand paces high each
of 20 000 persons that did inhabit Catania
3000 only did remain -

[page]41|MS-DAVY-11705-000-00041|dnp17e37pp|95148913[/page]
[deletion]The fire in its progress towards Catania[/deletion]
The fire in its progress, towards Catania
meet with a lake of 4 miles in compass and
it was not satisfied by filling it up though
it was four fathoms deep but it has made
a mountain of it
All the accounts that have been published
of eruptions in other parts of the world agree
in their general features, and from the
similarity of the[deletion]ir[/deletion] effects of [underline]Volcanic[/underline] fires
a strong conclusion may be formed concerning
the similarity of their causes. -
On this subject however a number of
difficulties [underline]oppose[/underline] themselves [underline]to our reasoning[/underline]

[page]42|MS-DAVY-11705-000-00042|dnp17e38pp|95148914[/page]
The agents concerned in those great
[underline]suberraneous changes[/underline] are hidden deep
in the bosom of the Earth and it is
impossible for us to contemplate them
in their [underline]active state.[/underline]
Even their effects can only be considered
at a distance and from the grandeur
and awful [underline]nature[/underline] of those [underline]effects[/underline] it
is ccarcely possible even for the most
philosophical and couragious mind to
examine with coolness and precision
Here analogy must be our principle
guide.

[page]43|MS-DAVY-11705-000-00043|dnp17e39pp|95148915[/page]
Analogy investigated with caution and
assisted by accurate experiment -
Many enquirers into nature in attempting
to account for volcanoes have [underline]supposed[/underline]
[underline]that[/underline] a permanent central fire occupying
the interior of the Earth is the universal
cause of igneous eruptions -
This notion is one which it requires
little depth of research to adopt and but
little acuteness of understanding fully to refute.
Heat in all its states is capable of being
communicated from body to body.
And if a permanent fire had been
acting for ages upon the interior of
the crust of the Globe its effects

[page]44|MS-DAVY-11705-000-00044|dnp17e40pp|95148916[/page]
must long ago have been perceived
upon the whole [underline]of that surface[/underline] which
would have exhibited not a few [deletion]evident[/deletion]
widely scattered Volcanoes but one
ignited and glowing mass -
An opinion infinitely [underline]more probable[/underline] is
that Volcanic fires are the result of chemical
changes of the intimate agencies of Bodies
of inflamable matters producing voilent
fermentations within the solid strata
|_ Lemery in 1670 was the first person who
brought forward this Theory und[insertion]er[/insertion] any precise
form and He founded it upon an
experiment of his own invention

